SIMPLE: mysticism
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mysticism
<hw>Mys"ti*cism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>mysticisme</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Obscurity of
doctrine.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Eccl. Hist.)</fld> <def>The doctrine of the
Mystics, who professed a pure, sublime, and wholly disinterested
devotion, and maintained that they had direct intercourse with the
divine Spirit, and aquired a knowledge of God and of spiritual things
unattainable by the natural intellect, and such as can not be analyzed
or explained.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Philos.)</fld> <def>The doctrine that the ultimate
elements or principles of knowledge or belief are gained by an act or
process akin to feeling or faith.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mystification</ent>⟦br⟧
